Using a hash map (unordered_map in C++) for string compression: iterate through the string, count consecutive occurrences of each character, and build a new string with character+count pairs. ```cpp
string compress(string s) {
    string result = "";
    int n = s.length();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ) {
        char ch = s[i];
        int count = 0;
        while (i < n && s[i] == ch) { i++; count++; }
        result += ch + to_string(count);
    }
    return result;
}
```
A hash map is more useful for counting non-consecutive character frequencies, while this run-length approach handles the classic "string compression" problem directly.
